FC: The Federal Court’s original jurisdiction to engage in judicial review under the Judiciary Act 1903 (Cth) and the Administrative Decisions (Judicial Review) Act 1977 (Cth); The jurisdiction conferred on the Federal Court by s 39B(1) of the Judiciary Act 1903 (Cth); 39B(1) says the original jurisdiction of the Federal Court of Australia includes jurisdiction with respect to any matter in which a writ of mandamus or prohibition or an injunction is sought against an officer or officers of the Commonwealth. Same test as constitution s75(v)
The jurisdiction conferred on the Federal Court by s 39B(1A)(c) of the Judiciary Act 1903 (Cth); The original jurisdiction of the Federal Court of Australia also includes jurisdiction in any matter: arising under any laws made by the Parliament. other than a matter in respect of which a criminal prosecution is instituted or any other criminal matter.
This reform: allows review of non-statutory executive powers (unlike the ADJR Act);
allows review of the validity of delegated/subordinate legislation (also not reviewable under the ADJRA Act);
