The counter argument is that this clause should be construed widely to include historical insolvency. This is because the purpose of RHOA s1(a)(ii) is to “reduce exploitative and undesirable practices”. Any person who has been insolvent tends to have bad judgement, thus more likely to engage in exploitative and undesirable conduct.
The better view is that this is unlikely to be an issue for Clive as the text of the statute is clear and insolvency is normally considered a financial failing, not a moral failing.
